aaData.4:
Our mobile devices have become as necessary and as ubiquitous as our wallets. These tiny pocket computers not only keep us connected, they store a lot of our personal information. Do you want to learn how to better protect the personal information on your mobile device? Find out with the Office of the Privacy Commissioner’s myPRIVACYapp. This app will walk you through ten simple steps to help better protect your privacy on your mobile device.

The Office of the Privacy Commissioner will not collect any personal information through this mobile app.

Before you start using this app, we encourage you to read through the end user license agreement (EULA) first. It’s not long – we promise.

For more information, visit our website at priv.gc.ca.

aaData.4:
The Rights and Responsibilities of Citizenship is the study guide for those preparing to meet the knowledge requirement to obtain Canadian citizenship. Discover Canada promotes to immigrants and Canadian citizens alike a greater understanding of Canada’s history, values, symbols and important Canadian institutions, such as Parliament and the Crown. It includes information on common values such as freedom, democracy, human rights, the rule of law and the equality of men and women. It also highlights the contribution of ethnic and cultural communities in shaping our Canadian identity and the sacrifices made by Canada’s veterans for our country.

The application also has a section on sample citizenship test questions.

aaData.0: McLaren's Workshop Close
aaData.3: A free iPad app that provides access to 51 works by animation pioneer Norman McLaren and lets users create their own films, exploring three animation techniques made famous by McLaren.
aaData.4:
The National Film Board of Canada (NFB) is proud to offer unparalleled access to the incomparable work of Norman McLaren, Canada’s best-known animation filmmaker.

McLaren’s animated films are landmarks in the history of cinema and have been celebrated around the world, winning an Oscar (Neighbours), a Palme d’Or in the short film category at Cannes (Blinkity Blank), a Berlin Silver Bear (Rythmetic), a Berlin Silver Plaque (Begone Dull Care), and several BAFTAs (Blinkity Blank, A Chairy Tale and Pas de deux).

The McLaren’s Workshop also gives users free access to 11 short documentaries that will guide them through McLaren’s impressive filmography, providing a thematic analysis of his work.

PAPER CUT-OUTS Workshop

Make your own animated films with the PAPER CUT-OUTS Workshop, using the paper elements and original backgrounds McLaren created when he animated his classic film Le merle.

SCRATCH ON FILM Workshop

The SCRATCH ON FILM Workshop allows you to scratch, draw and paint free-form images directly onto film frames, a technique McLaren made famous through inspired films like Blinkity Blank and Begone Dull Care. $2.99

SYNTHETIC SOUND Workshop

With this workshop, you can try your hand at the synthetic sound experiment McLaren undertook in his vibrant and award-winning Synchromy, whose music was created by drawing directly onto the soundtrack area of the film strip. $2.99

The McLaren’s Workshop requires iOS 5.1 and above.

Though it can be run on an iPad 1, we recommend using an iPad 2 to fully enjoy all the app's features.

KEY FEATURES

  • WATCH 51 films by Norman McLaren.
  • WATCH 11 short documentaries on Norman McLaren and his work.
  • WATCH LATER – Store films for up to 48 hours of off-line viewing.
  • MAKE YOUR OWN ANIMATION with the PAPER CUT-OUTS Workshop.
  • DRAW DIRECTLY ONTO FILM FRAMES with the SCRATCH ON FILM Workshop.
  • CREATE A MOVIE & SOUNDTRACK with the SYTHETIC SOUND Workshop.
  • READ an exclusive essay on McLaren’s works by Don McWilliams.
  • DISCOVER McLaren’s complete illustrated biography.

aaData.3: This interactive graphic novel follows a fictional family from Upper Canada that is torn apart by the conflict with the United States.
aaData.4:
Based on the book from Renegade Arts Entertainment and re-imagined for the iPad by the National Film Board of Canada, this immersive interactive graphic novel brings history to life.

The Loxleys and the War of 1812 follows a fictional family from Upper Canada torn apart by the conflict with the United States some 200 years ago.

Experience this key event in Canada’s history through journal entries, letters and beautifully animated, historically accurate illustrations by a team of award-winning comic book artists.

Features:

  • 80 pages of illustrations
  • captivating cinematic soundtrack
  • interactive map that pinpoints the action
  • educational study guide available on nfb.ca/1812/guide
  • comic written by Alan Grant
  • pencils and inks by Claude St. Aubin
  • letters by Todd Klein
  • colours by Lovern Kindzierski
  • historical research by Mark Zuehlke

Produced by the National Film Board of Canada in partnership with the Department of Canadian Heritage.

aaData.3: BARCODE is a simple and fun documentary app that gives voice to the objects around you.
aaData.4:
BARCODE is a simple and fun documentary app that gives voice to the objects around you. Enter the name of an object or scan its barcode, and the app will show you a 60-second film that just might change the way you look at that object.

With 100 short films directed by 30 Canadian and European filmmakers, BARCODE is a collective project that takes everyday objects out of the ordinary by seeing them in a whole new way. Each of the films is inspired by a different object, and offers a new perspective on it.

We invite you to participate by using the objects near you as a starting point to tell us your own stories about everyday items in your life. You can also find films and user-generated content based on location.

This app is a mobile extension of the interactive documentary CODEBARRE.TV, co-produced by the National Film Board of Canada and ARTE France, exploring who we are based on the objects that surround us.

Follow us: @codebarretv

www.codebarre.tv

aaData.3: The first made-for-tablet story that challenges the conventions of the tablet reading experience.
aaData.4:
The first made-for-tablet story that challenges the conventions of the tablet reading experience.

The Last Hunt features:

  • Smooth, intuitive scrolling that provides a seamless storytelling experience
  • A compelling narrative about family and tradition
  • Beautiful images by Montreal photographer Alexi Hobbs
  • Text overlaid with parallaxing interactive animation

Offering a new kind of interactive reading experience, The Last Hunt explores the strength of family bonds and the spirituality implicit in the act of hunting, delving deeply into the motivations that led Montreal photographer Alexi Hobbs to document his grandfather’s last hunting expedition.

To follow the story, which stretches from the present moment back to the Second World War, app users scroll vertically through text overlaid with delicate, parallaxing interactive animation that challenges the conventions of the tablet reading experience.

aaData.3: The ourlanguages.gc.ca on the go! mobile application lets users search TERMIUM Plus®, the Government of Canada's terminology and linguistic data bank, and quickly find equivalents for nearly 4 million English and French terms in various fields.
aaData.4:
ourlanguages.gc.ca on the go! is the Government of Canada’s first mobile linguistic application. Developed by the Translation Bureau (www.btb.gc.ca), it lets you search TERMIUM Plus®, the Government of Canada’s terminology and linguistic data bank.

TERMIUM Plus®, the Language Portal of Canada’s flagship product, is:

  • one of the largest linguistic data banks in the world, containing nearly 4 million acronyms, abbreviations, and technical and highly specialized terms, as well as the Government of Canada’s official terminology in English and French;
  • a bilingual dictionary to find the precise English or French equivalents for many terms in various fields;
  • a unilingual dictionary to verify the meaning of highly specialized terms not found in most standard dictionaries;
  • a collection of emerging English and French terminology in nearly every field of human endeavour. The Language Portal of Canada (www.ourlanguages.gc.ca) is a website that showcases Canadian expertise in language—a one-stop source for information on language and writing, quizzes, writing tools and many other resources dealing with different aspects of English and French.

An Internet connection is required to use this application. This application supports both English and French and will choose the appropriate language based on your device's settings. To run this application in French please switch your device into French mode and restart the application.

aaData.3: Edifica is your own personal guide to uncovering the history of Canada. You can access stories, historical facts, descriptions, images and links to historic places recognized for their local, provincial and national importance.
aaData.4:
Edifica is your own personal guide to uncovering the historic places of Canada’s beautiful port cities: Victoria, Québec City and Halifax, as well as the major sites of the War of 1812. With Edifica, you can access stories, historical facts, descriptions, images and links to over 700 historic places officially recognized for their local, provincial and national importance.

As your handy travel guide, whether touring in person or virtually, Edifica will give you insight into the unique, striking and wondrous historic places that add character to local neighbourhoods, downtowns, and bustling ports.

Edifica is the first mobile app developed by Canada’s Historic Places, a successful federal-provincial-territorial partnership dedicated to creating the definitive register of all historic places in Canada officially recognized for their heritage value. The entire Register is available online at www.historicplaces.ca.

Bring Canada's national historic sites and the best of Canadian heritage cooking into your home with the Parks Canada Heritage Gourmet food app. Embark on a culinary journey through Canada’s rich history and across Canada’s vast territory by trying out the recipes – which have been updated for modern cooks - and reading the stories in this app.

  • Choose from over 70 recipes, each with a stunning photograph of the finished dish.
  • Browse recipes from the 18th century to today, representing all of Canada's regions.
  • Enjoy traditional recipes that have been chef-tested and modified for today's cooks, with both imperial and metric measures.
  • Search or browse by ingredient, course, menu, period or region.
  • The app is self-contained - no internet connection is required after the initial download and periodic updates.

Save recipes to your personal recipe collection.

  • Add ingredients to your Shopping List to bring with you to the grocery store.
  • Share recipes with friends and family using email, Facebook and Twitter.
  • Cook traditional favourites like Acadan Bouilli, West Coast Finnan Haddie and Newfoundland’s Jiggs Dinner.
  • Enjoy national historic site tried-and-true favourites like the Fortress of Louisbourg’s French Soldier's Bread, Woodside’s Marmalade or Lower Fort Garry's famous Corn Bread
  • Try out recipes like Bannock, Luski and Sourdough Flapjacks that were originally cooked over an outdoor fire.
  • Cook an entire meal using one of the menus.
  • Learn a story about each recipe - tell your dinner guests or family which notable Canadian enjoyed a particular dish, how a dish got its name or which 18th century cookbook a recipe first came from.
  • Watch a behind-the-scenes video of the chefs and photographers at work.
  • See a video of chefs creating an 18th century dessert using today's ingredients.
  • Find out about the national historic site of Canada that submitted the recipe and start to plan your next culinary adventure.

aaData.3: Explora at the Lachine Canal is a companion which reveals the rich industrial heritage of the canal, the cradle of industrialization in Canada.
aaData.4:
Explora at the Lachine Canal is a companion which reveals the rich industrial heritage of the canal, the cradle of industrialization in Canada. Seven GPS-based tours are designed to help you discover the secrets and stories of the Lachine Canal, nearby buildings, and the people who lived this history firsthand.

Explora at the Lachine Canal app includes stories, archived photos, 2D and 3D animations providing technical information or showing the evolution of the landscape, detailed maps and more. As visitors stroll or boat along the canal, they will enjoy this entertaining and richly informative experience.

Located in Montreal, the Lachine Canal runs 14.5 kilometers from the Old Port to Lake Saint-Louis. Its history stretches over more than 150 years. It comes within the scope of the interdependence between shipping, industrialization and urbanization, which marked Montréal’s development.

The resources on OSI Connect address challenges including post-traumatic stress and triggers, depression, anger, sleep problems, substance abuse, stress management and more.

Developed by the Royal Ottawa OSI Clinic with the support of Veterans Affairs Canada, this app is compatible with iPhone, iPad, iPod, BlackBerry and Android devices. OSI Connect is a regularly updated, information rich, interactive mobile application. There are assessments, videos and clear information for Veterans and others with an OSI, including how to get an OSI clinic appointment.
